European inflation has declined in food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dramatic growth in the price of food products.
The price increase in November has been higher than expected in the 13 euro area countries, recording - after 2.6 per cent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, along with the rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to maintain the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: - we have to negotiate - on inflation so that it will not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, registered in Germany, struck the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Inflation was spread in the euro area as a result of the galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat prices increased by 88 per cent and soy prices reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil on the world market increased this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold almost $100 per barrel last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 percent current to 2.5 percent, but by 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will be maintained in the next 3 to 4 months about 3 percent, yet the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
