In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year a number of thousands of infections first produced by the misuse of antibiotics have been registered in hospitals.
The prevailing hygiene circumstances in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overcrowding of staff do not favor the control of infections - says the head doctor of department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an infection with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
An injured car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient had to return to the hospital as a result of MRSA infection and since then there has been no significant surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection by multi-resistant agents have been recorded in the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance - said Karolina Böröcz, head of department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that the number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded in hospitals, and there is no information available.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
One third of human beings carry in their nose Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria without causing any disease.
Infections produced by SA (e.g., inflammation of the throat, tonsilitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easily treated.
However, once antibiotics are exaggerated or improperly applied, bacteria that usually react well to antibiotics become very resistant bacteria and quickly become infected with inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause severe hospital infections, such as injury infections or sepsis in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with weakened organism, to elderly people or to those with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection with the epidemic should not be confused, the MRSA is only absent - Tibor Nyulasi said - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistance
These patients are isolated, the nursing staff attends them on rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment,\" Tibor Nyulasi said.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but not even so can infection be prevented in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent MRSA hospital infections in most cases, but current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of training and infection with multi-resistant pathogens - Karolina Böröcz says.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and homes of elderly people, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, taking microbiological samples is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come out in public when MRSA infections are already occurring visible in the patient - said the chief physician of department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes strict orders for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological pictures.
Antibiotic therapy should be undertaken, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological samples are even less frequent in the case of walking patients or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is infected from one patient to another through health personnel.
They therefore play a very important role in hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks, but in this regard there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA was contagious by means of droplet transmission and direct contact between individuals, however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Furthermore, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated for at least a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, it can also be experienced - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favourable economic situation it saves with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a greater likelihood of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate prevention measures are carried out, fewer such infections are recorded or the pathogen may be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to have success, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a tendency to decrease in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
