EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
The Hungarian finance minister János Veres and the vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed three credit-limit agreements in Budapest on Friday for a total amount of EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out from the grant of cohesion funds, of which the parties had already signed a credit contract of a value of EUR 100 million, the contract that they have just signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved EUR 300 million in total for this objective in Hungary, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later, by extending the credit agreement.
The parties signed a contract of EUR 50 million for innovations, which the budget will use primarily for the project of innovations and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the theme of the construction of the 4th metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the financing of the Metro, they will again address the issue of whether or not to modify the original contract and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990 the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the loans is in line with EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging commission for keeping the credit available to the debtor.
