The meeting at the expert level will be concluded on Tuesday and Wednesday following the official inauguration, as reported by the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor, will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the post-2012 international climate regime.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries of the world are discussing the Bali Road Map, which provides for post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the particulars between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not wish to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to reach an agreement that, compared to the situation in 1990, until 2020, it decreases the emission of greenhouse gases by 25 to 40 per cent.
Another major theme of the conference is that if industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to provide material and technological assistance to countries in need.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
