The six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to retain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement until 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing by 2020, with respect to the 1990 level by 20 percent its greenhouse gas emissions, regardless of whether or not the post-2012 agreement will be signed, and is willing to commit to decreasing even 30 percent if the other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are also ready to take on commitments in line with their responsibility and capacities.
Gábor Fodor noted that the 1997 Kyoto Protocol's signatory countries committed themselves to decreasing by 5.2 per cent, in which case the 15 EU Member States then committed themselves to meeting 8 per cent of decline.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce by 6 percent the greenhouse gas emissions from the period 1985 to 87, which our country will comply with - reports the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
Much is at stake in Balí, since the international long-term climate policy agreement will have to be signed within two years, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force will be postponed by the end of 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system, the need for which was warned in its latest IPCC report, the UN international scientific partnership dealing with climate change, which was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
As a result, the reduction in emissions would be delayed and an increase of more than 2°C of the average temperature of the Earth could not be prevented, which scientists say would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
British Army Recruits YouTube · Global Voices
British Army units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube services: the special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general operating body of Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable
There are 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been loaded on the Internet and their channel has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in spring 2007 under the name of “defence headsquarters” and publishes videos of both actions carried out in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the British Nations Community (Commonwealth Office) and multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruiting objectives, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defense also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda is practically nothing compared to conventional television recruiting spots - the BBC has been told the defence expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the carefully edited and censored recordings, there are also popular videos in the distributor, for example about the death of soldiers: in the propaganda films - officers - a little hypocritical, the officers speak of maximum losses, without presenting yet the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded to the Internet, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with video shooting games, downloadable for free, called America's Army, in which in the midst of a more or less real situation the player can be put directly in place of the soldiers.
