In parallel with its parliamentary procedure, which today ended with the Congress's vote on the amendments incorporated into the Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the rules that will develop the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
Representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members and Senators to negotiate and consensualize the best legislation in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activity of the entities for the markets to function efficiently.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new legislation will provide financial advisory services to both specialized firms and natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial services (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI), which join stock companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of operations on financial instruments, so that the regulated secondary markets add to the multilateral trading systems and the internalization of orders, which will compete with the current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment service companies to disseminate information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management and requires them to register all operations they carry out, in order to facilitate oversight by the CNV.
In its passage through the Economic Commission of Congress, a number of amendments were incorporated, including the fact that the debt-titled is considered a financial instrument - a complex one - given its high risk for the investor, which has been demonstrated by the debt of high-risk US mortgages (subprime).
