Venus: Twin brother of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to the Earth, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe - Venus Express - discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds on the poles, the same that appear also in winter on Earth.
For the past three decades, researchers had suspected that there might be rays in Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. In Venus the street rays of a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles tells the scientific journal \"Nature\"
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller's origin of life, the rays caused life on Earth: the storms could have caused reactions in the ocean which, on the other hand, had given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
Venus is not like this: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution - says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500°C, oscillating so that low temperatures can be reached.
\"Perhaps, Venus is a \"diabolic\" twin from Earth, but it's still a twin,\" Russell said.
The main objective of the mission - Venus Express - is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since there had been no special missions since the 1990s, only for research on this planet, the launch of “Venus Express” in November 2005 was a very important step for the investigation of Venus.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of \"Nature\" according to researchers' opinion, highlight not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with Earth than we had supposed to have,” says ESA.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost so large.
This planet also called the star of dawn or evening star orbits around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day in Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and with its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not resemble the Earth very much, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets, water on the Earth remained in the oceans, but in Venus it was dissociated in the universe.
While carbon dioxide had become carbon stones on Earth, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
